{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"32c985ef-6fa8-477d-bbb3-052cf0e08ece","content":"## What happened\n\n**DSA was fully removed on macOS in .NET 11.** This is the culmination of a multi-version deprecation:\n\n1. **.NET 7** — `DSA.Create()` and related APIs were marked obsolete with warning **SYSLIB0017**.\n2. **.NET 10** — Still worked on macOS via an OpenSSL-based fallback (`DSAOpenSsl`), since Apple's Security framework has never supported DSA natively.\n3. **.NET 11** — The fallback was removed. `DSA.Create()` now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS.\n\nOn **Linux** (OpenSSL) and **Windows** (CNG) the call still succeeds—only macOS is affected.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nYou have three options, from quickest to best:\n\n### Option 1 — Use `DSAOpenSsl` explicitly (quick fix)\nIf OpenSSL is installed on macOS (e.g. via Homebrew):\n\n```csharp\nusing System.Security.Cryptography;\n\nDSA dsa;\nif (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())\n    dsa = new DSAOpenSsl();       // requires OpenSSL on the machine\nelse\n    dsa = DSA.Create();\n\ndsa.ImportSubjectPublicKeyInfo(publicKeyBytes, out _);\nbool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA1);\n```\n\n> ⚠️ This ties your macOS builds to a Homebrew/OpenSSL dependency.\n\n### Option 2 — Use BouncyCastle (portable, no native dependency)\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\nvar verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA1withDSA\");\nvar pubKey   = PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyBytes);\nverifier.Init(forSigning: false, pubKey);\nverifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);\nbool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);\n```\n\nThis works everywhere with zero platform dependencies.\n\n### Option 3 — Migrate away from DSA (recommended long-term)\n\nDSA is a legacy algorithm. If you control the signing side, re-sign with **ECDSA** or **Ed25519**, both of which are fully supported on all platforms:\n\n```csharp\nusing var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create(ECCurve.NamedCurves.nistP256);\n```\n\n## Recommendation\n\nUse **Option 2** (BouncyCastle) to unblock your builds now, and plan **Option 3** (algorithm migration) for the long term. Avoid suppressing SYSLIB0017—it exists precisely to signal this removal trajectory.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d0fc14d8-846e-4dcf-b717-fcd21b9a6531","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me think about what I know about this topic.\n\nThis is a well-known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7+, Microsoft has been deprecating and removing older cryptographic algorithms. Specifically:\n\nIn .NET 7, several older cryptographic algorithms were marked as obsolete with warnings (SYSLIB0017 for DSA's Create methods).\n\nBut more critically, **Apple's Security framework (on macOS)** dropped support for DSA. Since .NET on macOS uses Apple's native crypto libraries (via the `System.Security.Cryptography` namespace using platform-native implementations), DSA operations fail on macOS.\n\n\nLet me clarify the timeline here. The issue with DSA on macOS actually started earlier than I initially thought—Apple removed DSA support from their Security framework, which means `DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS regardless of the .NET version. Since the user is upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11, I should verify the release timeline to understand what versions we're actually dealing with. So the most likely explanation is that Microsoft removed the software fallback for DSA on macOS in .NET 11, since the platform has been trending toward deprecating legacy cryptographic algorithms and Apple's native frameworks don't support DSA anyway. method tries to use the platform's native crypto provider, but macOS doesn't have native DSA support. In newer .NET versions, `DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS because the fallback implementations were removed. I can suggest a few workarounds: explicitly using `DSAOpenSsl` if OpenSSL is available, switching to a third-party library like BouncyCastle, or migrating to a modern algorithm like ECDSA or Ed25519 if possible. to BouncyCastle, or migrate to a modern signature algorithm like ECDSA or EdDSA instead.","outputTokens":2108,"requestId":"680C:2636C7:288CCD0:2C766BD:69FD297E"},"id":"c7fb4a38-e174-4e8a-b79a-ef86a9ac19b6","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:09:17.670Z","parentId":"7852d440-4d46-40aa-8055-3e9d9f3a954a"}
